<span id="freeTextContainer12573440011163990805">Years ago, I was on jury duty in LA. This was back when jury duty largely consisted of waiting around in a large room each day for a week. I brought along a copy of The Histories (the Rawlinson translation published by Everyman&apos;s Library) and found myself engrossed by all the stories, tall tales, gossip, rumors, etc. It&apos;s a wonderful panoply that&apos;s on offer here! Sure, Herodotus was criticized by many for not writing &quot;facts,&quot; but the power of stories is far greater, and he knew it.</span>
  <span id="freeText12573440011163990805" style="display:none">Years ago, I was on jury duty in LA. This was back when jury duty largely consisted of waiting around in a large room each day for a week. I brought along a copy of The Histories (the Rawlinson translation published by Everyman's Library) and found myself engrossed by all the stories, tall tales, gossip, rumors, etc. It's a wonderful panoply that's on offer here! Sure, Herodotus was criticized by many for not writing "facts," but the power of stories is far greater, and he knew it.</span>
